25
00:03:38,060 --> 00:03:48,980
Here need to wind in several layers, so went experimentally toward reducing wire section and stopped in optimal mode.

26
00:03:49,120 --> 00:03:56,980
That is this core wound fully around circumference in one layer.

27
00:03:57,160 --> 00:04:10,340
Before start of work on winding wire on this core, won't be superfluous to calculate total wire length that will fit on this magnetic core.

28
00:04:10,720 --> 00:04:26,080
For this use known formula of calculating circumference length, expressed through diameter, where P — circumference length, π — constant 3.14 and D — diameter.

29
00:04:26,940 --> 00:04:32,860
Measure with caliper this diameter and substitute it in formula.

30
00:04:33,360 --> 00:04:39,100
Multiply, get circumference length 42.39 mm.

31
00:04:39,900 --> 00:04:45,240
Further need to stop at wire diameter that we'll wind.

32
00:04:45,300 --> 00:04:48,060
In this case at me this 0.35 mm.

33
00:04:48,820 --> 00:04:50,200
Further act so.

34
00:04:50,860 --> 00:04:55,640
Circumference length divide by wire diameter, get turn count.

35
00:04:55,980 --> 00:05:00,760
121 turn will fit on this core.

36
00:05:01,180 --> 00:05:04,140
Now should know length of one turn.

37
00:05:04,240 --> 00:05:08,320
For this tightly wrap core with wire, straighten and measure.

38
00:05:08,860 --> 00:05:12,400
In this case turn length at me made 21 mm.

39
00:05:13,120 --> 00:05:22,160
Now multiply turn count by length of one turn and get wire length in millimeters.

40
00:05:22,700 --> 00:05:30,980
Further divide by 1000 mm in one meter and express length already in meters.

41
00:05:31,160 --> 00:05:35,060
In my case made 2.54 mm.

42
00:05:35,820 --> 00:05:39,380
Approximately with leads I took 2.6 mm.

43
00:05:40,180 --> 00:05:48,000
